Abstract
Change: a phrase-based statistical system with a bigram language model and beam-search decoding 
To: a phrase-based statistical trigram language model and a log-linear stack decoder
Change: our phrase-based system achieves 5.22 BLEU To: our phrase-based system achieves 12.35 BLEU
add to: “planned extensions including larger training sets, improved alignment, and an IBM Model 2 baseline", re-evaluation of test set to be part of europarl corpus

Methods §2.2 — Phrase-based SMT
Change: Phrase table built from a position-ratio heuristic, $L_{\max}=4$, min count 2, top 5 translations To: Phrase table built from consistent-with-alignment extraction (Och 1999) using fast_align + gdfa symmetrized alignments, $L_{\max}=3$, top 20 translations
Change: Two features stored per phrase pair (phrase probability, normalized counts) To: Four Moses-style log-linear features: $\phi(\bar e\mid\bar f)$, $\phi(\bar f\mid\bar e)$, $\mathrm{lex}(\bar e\mid\bar f,a)$, $\mathrm{lex}(\bar f\mid\bar e,a)$ with NULL-aware lexical translation tables
Change: Bigram language model with add-one (Laplace) smoothing To: Trigram language model with stupid backoff ($\alpha = 0.4$)
Change: Monotonic beam-search decoder, beam size 12, scored as $\log P_\text{phrase} + \lambda \log P_\text{LM}$, $\lambda=0.35$, unknown words passed through verbatim To: Log-linear stack decoder (Pharaoh/Moses style): coverage-bitmap stacks, distortion limit 2, beam 32, up to 4 options per span, hypothesis recombination on (coverage, last end, last 2 LM words), future-cost DP for pruning, six feature weights set by hand with MERT tuning planned

